To verify the deterministic Quick Sort in Verus, we define a property `is_bounded_perm(v1, v2, start, end)` which states that `v2` is a permutation of `v1` where the permutation index map is the identity outside the range `[start, end)`. This allows us to frame the effects of `partition` and recursive calls to `qs_rec` on specific sub-slices of the array, proving that they do not disturb the sortedness or values of the rest of the array.

We implement the `partition` function using the first element as the pivot (Lomuto partition scheme variant). We prove that `partition` permutes the array within the bounds `[start, end)` such that elements smaller than the pivot are to the left of the returned index `p`, and elements greater or equal are to the right.

The `qs_rec` function recursively sorts the left and right partitions. The termination is guaranteed by the decreasing measure `end - start`. Since `partition` returns `p` strictly within `[start, end)` (provided `end - start >= 2`), the recursive calls `qs_rec(start, p)` and `qs_rec(p+1, end)` operate on strictly smaller slices.

